'''Seigen-ji''' (聖現寺, せいげんじ) is a temple of the {{ill|Tōji Shingon Sect|ja|東寺真言宗|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Okinawa Prefecture|ja|沖縄県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Naha City|ja|那覇市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== History ==
According to tradition, during the {{ill|Seika|ja|成化|qq=draft|qq=draft}} period (1465–1487), the temple was founded (kaizan) by {{ill|Dokukai Zenji|ja|咄海禅師|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Originally established as a temple of the {{ill|Rinzai Sect|ja|臨済宗|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it converted to the {{ill|Shingon Sect|ja|真言宗|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in 1671 (the 10th year of the {{ill|Kangxi|ja|康熙|qq=draft|qq=draft}} era) under the auspices of {{ill|Raichō Hōin|ja|頼昌法印|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and in 1734 (the 12th year of the {{ill|Yongzheng|ja|雍正|qq=draft|qq=draft}} era) the Tenkyū-gu was relocated. This temple also serves as the bettō (administrative temple) of Tenkyū-gu.<ref name="観光">[https://www.naha-contentsdb.jp/spot/443 "Seigen-ji"] Naha City "Naha City Tourism Resource Database"</ref><ref name="百科">Okinawa Daihyakka Jiten, Vol.2: "Ke-To", published by Okinawa Times-sha, 1983, p.546</ref>.

It suffered catastrophic damage during the Battle of Okinawa in 1945 (Showa 20) and was rebuilt in 1958.<ref name="百科"></ref>

== Access ==
* An 8‑minute walk from the Uenoya bus stop (【路線バス】).

